<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much Benadryl can I give my dog?", answer: "The standard veterinary dosage for Benadryl (diphenhydramine) in dogs is 2-4 mg per kilogram of body weight, given every 8-12 hours. For a 50-pound (22.7 kg) dog, that is approximately 45-91 mg per dose. Standard Benadryl tablets are 25 mg, so a 50-pound dog would take 2-3 tablets. Always use plain diphenhydramine without added decongestants or alcohol, and consult your vet before giving any medication." },
  { question: "Can I give my cat human medication?", answer: "Some human medications can be given to cats at veterinarian-approved doses, but many are extremely dangerous. Cats lack certain liver enzymes that break down common drugs. For example, acetaminophen (Tylenol) is lethal to cats even in small doses. Benadryl and Pepcid can be given to cats at specific doses, but always verify with your veterinarian first. Never assume a human medication is safe for cats." },
  { question: "How do I calculate medication dosage by pet weight?", answer: "Medication dosages are typically expressed in milligrams per kilogram (mg/kg) of body weight. To calculate: convert your pet's weight from pounds to kilograms by multiplying by 0.4536. Then multiply the weight in kg by the mg/kg dosage. For example, a 30-pound dog weighs 13.6 kg. At a dosage of 2 mg/kg, the dose would be 27.2 mg." },
  { question: "What is the difference between minimum and maximum dose?", answer: "The minimum dose is the lowest effective amount, typically recommended for starting treatment or for mild symptoms. The maximum dose is the highest safe amount per administration. Veterinarians usually recommend starting at the lower end of the range and only increasing if needed and tolerated. Never exceed the maximum dose without veterinary guidance, as overdoses can cause serious side effects." },
  { question: "Should I consult a vet before giving my pet medication?", answer: "Yes, always consult your veterinarian before giving any medication, even over-the-counter supplements. Your vet can account for your pet's specific health conditions, other medications they are taking, and potential drug interactions. Some conditions (like liver or kidney disease) require dose adjustments. This calculator provides general guidelines based on standard veterinary dosing, but individual pets may have different needs." }
]) %>

